			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Mass Kiting - Feedback Requested!!<a name="19822"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 8 04 6:35 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hiya Fellow Bards!!
<br />

<br />
I've just recently started a bard and I am playing him up starting on a new server.  Keep that in mind when I talk about some of the stuff below.  I have no twinkage gear and I'm mostly decked out in my Bardologist newbie armor.  I commonly see listings of the kiting types employed by bards but I rarely see reference to what I've been calling Mass Kiting or as I joke about it, Drive-By Kiting (not to be confused with Swarm Kiting which is fairly well defined on these pages).  I am now 18th level but I've gotten here almost exclusively by kiting.  If this form of kiting isn't in the guides section already (I've read the ones I thought might be related but I could have missed some) I'd like your feedback on this technique plus some input as to how you think this will work at higher levels.  I was first introduced to this technique by an older and wiser bard on my server named Ziyona Sawiki although she ran in better circles than I do (figuratively as well as literally!).  So if you're reading this Zi, thank you for opening my eyes to this fantastic technique!
<br />

<br />
Abbreviation Key:
<br />

<br />
DD:  Direct Damage
<br />
AoE:  Area of Effect
<br />
DoT:  Damage over Time
<br />
xp:  Experience!
<br />

<br />
To try to simplify the technique, I'll sort of arrange it in steps:
<br />

<br />
Step1:  Find a group of non-casting mobs, socially aware mobs.  Very important step as even a comparably low level caster mob can royally screw you if you aggro it (see below in my description of hunting areas for lowbie bards).  The mobs you kite can be as high as 3 levels above you (or higher really, but I'm not sure the xp is worth the time and risk).  Having them in close proximity is a bonus.
<br />

<br />
Step2:  Set up your first hot button for Selo's (or use sow, I guess) and your second one with your current AoE DoT.  Put your Hymn of Restoration on a third button and, if you've got it, put your Bellow or other DD song on a fourth.  I recommend that the buttons at the bottom of that Hot Button window be used to enable fast instrument switching.  At level 18 you can sneak your second AoE DoT onto the third button, bumping the heal song to number four.
<br />

<br />
Step3:  Identify a good pull-to area: i.e. an area that is reasonably flat and open with plenty of running room.  Check the vicinity for the types of mobs that typically wander there and don't forget to figure them into your equation!  Some don't matter too much but most you'll want to avoid while kiting.
<br />

<br />
Step4:  The Gathering.  Start out with your stringed instrument equipped (if using Chords of Dissonance) or your Brass instrument (if using Denon's Disruptive Discord) and have Selo's going.  You'll be keeping this equipped most of the time.  Run around gathering up the group to be kited.  Depending on faction status, you may have to hit the first with Bellow but the others should all aggro on you after that.  Run around and gather up 5 - 15 or so (by the way, I don't know if there is an upper limit to the number of mobs...I've done about 15 or so but I don't see why more wouldn't also work). Run around them a few times in a rough circle and bunch them up.  This is pretty easy to do.
<br />

<br />
Step5:  The Delivery.  In your kite area, pick two points that are recognizable to you.  I have, when desperate, actually used the compass point for this, but its definitely easier to maintain your concentration if you go by landmarks.  Another thing you can do is look at the texture lines for direction on the ground.  Start out running toward one landmark.  As you begin to get near it, start casting your DoT and then bank around, fairly quickly, about 180 degrees.  Never stop your forward motion, just turn to the left or right.  Usually, you can aim for a turn to be finished in 4 key presses (I do this because it enables me to achieve better timing and it forces me to take my time and hold my form).  The key here is that you want your song to finish casting at the time you finish your turn.  Another key is that as you finish your turn, you should be facing roughly your 2nd landmark.  If done right, you should be just beyond the melee range of the mobs but they will be within range of your AoE DoT.  So they should all get hit by your DoT and you should remain free to go!  This first blast of the mobs has taken me several go-rounds to hit.  I think it has to do with getting them the right distance away but I'm concentrating too hard to care about it at the time.
<br />

<br />
Step6:  After delivering the first blast, hit your Selo's key to maintain your speed while you head toward your 2nd landmark.  When Selo's finishes casting, start Step5 over again by beginning your cast of your DoT again.  Starting at level 18, you can alternate in your two DoTs because they stack rather well.  All you need to do is repeat Steps 5 and 6 for about 10 - 15 minutes and you'll have a dozen dead yellow mobs lying about.  
<br />

<br />
Obviously, this technique leads to crazy xp accumulation and delusions of power and grandeur.  This is normal.  Don't worry that as you Selo's your way to your next destination and you pass a lonely Beastlord solo fighting a mere one or two blue mobs you feel a sense of superiority.  Maintain your composure as you watch a leet young druid on her first quad-kite.  This is one of the many reasons why I so love my bard so far!!
<br />

<br />
Suggestions as to where to hunt:
<br />

<br />
At level 5, head to Shadeweaver's Thicket.  To the West of Shar Vahl there is a plateau between two roads.  All around this area are mobs called Gor Taku Scouts and other varieties.  You can also hunt the Shak Dratha as well.  They are often found in clumps of rocks to the South.  I did these until about level 10.  The nice thing about these two groups is that they are on opposite faction so you don’t have to worry about wrecking it, if you care.  Watch out for a mob called &quot;a nuisance&quot;!!!  Let me tell you, they are.  They are only level 1 or 3 or something, but they are casters and will break your songs and rhythms.
<br />

<br />
At level 10, I went further west following the road.  There is a cave up there with Gor Taku Guards guarding the entrance.  To the left and right of this entrance are two clumps of rocks which spawn Gor Taku Hunters and Shak Dratha Assassins.  Those 6 plus the two workers to the west of the Northern rock outcropping got me to about level 14.  The spawn time is longer for these, so in between I was kiting other things as well.
<br />

<br />
At level 14, go next door to the other cave entrance.  This cave hosts a huge gathering of Loda Kai poachers and traders, and, wouldn’t you know it, they are highly aggressive and sociable AND they are all together on a wide, broad, open floored cavern<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />  I hunted here until about 16.
<br />

<br />
At level 16, I went deeper into the caverns and found a big cavern at about neg 1400, pos 750.  This hosted a bunch of Gor Taku Sentrys and Bruisers.  Probably 15 mobs or so.  The best part is that they are replaced with Shak Dratha equivalent when you kill them so your faction remains about the same.  At level 16 these were all yellow or red for the most part.  The Shak Dratha Shawi spawns here and is much higher level (23 - 26 according to EQBeastiary).  Its still possible to kill, and I have.  It just takes a while and patience.
<br />

<br />
That's where I'm at so far.  That last place I mentioned does spawn casters, it's just rare.  So keep that in mind before starting your kite.
<br />

<br />
Again, thanks for taking the time to read this and let me know if you have any thoughtful feedback.  I plan on taking this technique to higher levels and want to know if anyone else has tried it and if so what sort of places you've hunted, etc.
<br />

<br />
Take care and hunt safe!
<br />

<br />
Mevendien
<br />

<br />
Bard of the 18th Song</span></td>
